    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1928-03-29T17:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1928-03-29T17:00:00-05:00" n="335"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d335">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">711.5612A/3: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of State</gloss> to
                        the Minister in the Netherlands</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Tobin</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1928-03-29T17:00:00-05:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">March 29, 1928—5 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>11. The Department handed the Chargé d’Affaires of the Netherlands Legation,
                    today, a draft of a proposed treaty of arbitration between the United States and
                    the Netherlands.<note n="29" xml:id="d335fn29">Draft not printed.</note> The
                    provisions of the draft operate to extend the policy of arbitration enunciated
                    in the Convention signed at Washington, May 2, 1908,<note n="30"
                        xml:id="d335fn30">
                        <ref target="frus1909#pg_442">
                            <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1909, p. 442</ref>.</note>
                    which expires on March 25, 1929. The language of the draft is identical in
                    effect with that of the Arbitration Treaty recently signed with France<note
                        n="31" xml:id="d335fn31">
                        <ref target="frus1928v02#pg_816">Vol. <hi rend="smallcaps">ii</hi>, p.
                            816</ref>.</note> and with the draft arbitration treaties already
                    submitted to other governments in the general program for the extension of these
                    principles. The text of the proposed treaty will be forwarded in the next
                    pouch.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Olds</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
